{"section_content":"This section introduces our proposed DGF-PT framework, as shown in Figure 2. We frst design the prompt-based autoregressive encoder to acquire the fne-grained representations (entity pair, object, and text), which contains two types of prefxes for integrating helpful information and characterizing intra-modal and inter-modal interactions. To avoid unhelpful visual information misleading the model, we design the dual-gated fusion module to distinguish the importance of image\/objects via local and global gates. It also integrates the semantics of image transferred by Oscar (Li et al., 2020). The Fusion module outputs an enhanced representation. Later, the generative decoder is proposed for relation prediction, leveraging the implicit associations and restricting candidate relations by introducing entity types. Finally, we design the joint objective including distribution-consistency constraint, self-identifcation enhancement, and relation classifcation for model optimization.\nGiven text $T$ , the word embeddings $\\mathbf{w}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{1\\times N}$ are obtained through the GPT-2 model (Radford et al., 2019) and then fed into a fully-connection layer, where $N$ is the word dimension. The initial text representation is T = [w1; w2; . . . ; wL] \u2208 RL\u00d7N .\nGiven an image $I$ , the global image feature $\\mathbf{I}\\in$ $\\mathbb{R}^{M\\times N}$ is obtained by VGG16 (Simonyan and Zisserman, 2015) with a fully-connection layer, transferring the feature into $M$ -block $N$ -dimensional vectors. We then extract object features using Faster R-CNN (Ren et al., 2015) and select top$K$ objects using the ROI classifcation score. Each object feature is obtained by the average grouping of ROI regions. The initial object representation is O = [o1; o2; . . . ; oK] \u2208 RK\u00d7N ."}
{"section_content":"Utilizing the advantages of prefx-tuning, the pretrained encoder (e.g., GPT-2 as our encoder) can be guided to learn task-specifc features for fast adaptation to the MMRE task (Liu et al., 2021). However, the design of appropriate prefxes for fner associations learning in the MMRE task remains an open research question, and the direct use of prefxes from other tasks is not reasonable. Therefore, we construct two types of prefxes, an object-oriented prefx for inter-modal relevance (objects & text) and an entity-oriented prefx for intra-modal correlations (entity pair & text), encouraging the encoder to leverage text as a medium to strengthen multigranular associations to acquire enhanced semantic representations.\n\nObject-Oriented Prefx. Given that objects related to entities are indeed useful information for the MMRE task, we propose an object-oriented prefx, termed as $\\mathcal{P}_{o}(\\cdot)$ , which provides guidance information of inter-modal relevance to the encoder. For the input text $T$ , we defne the following pattern \u201cConsider $\\langle o b j e c t s\\rangle$ , predict relation.\u201d, where $\\langle o b j e c t s\\rangle$ means the objects relevant to the entity pair of $T$ which is different for each input. It emphasizes specifc key textual contents and introduces the visual features of relevant objects.\nEntity-Oriented Prefx. Due to the visual information may be incomplete or misleading, we argue that only an object-oriented prefx is insuffcient to capture classifcation information. Thus, we propose an entity-oriented prefx, termed as $\\mathcal{P}_{e}(\\cdot)$ , to capture intra-modal association to adapt the task. We defne the following pattern \u201cConsider $\\langle e_{1},e_{2}\\rangle$ , predict relation.\u201d, where $\\langle e_{1},e_{2}\\rangle$ is the entity pair to predict the relation."}

